### District Judge Luke Tan:

## Introduction

1       The accused, Soo Cheow Wee, is a 50-year-old Singaporean male.

2       Before me, he faced a total of eight charges, four of which he pleaded guilty to (“**_proceeded charges_**”), and the remaining four charges were taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing (“**_TIC charges_**”). The four proceeded charges related to incidents that took place in 2022 and 2019, while the TIC charges involved incidents that occurred in 2022 and 2021. The broad details of the proceeded charges and TIC charges are summarised below.

3       For this case, the Prosecution sought a sentence of at least five years of corrective training (CT), or alternatively a global sentence of 57 to 63 months’ imprisonment to be imposed. Counsel for the accused originally indicated that the sentence imposed should not be more than 1 year’s imprisonment, although counsel subsequently confirmed that they were not sticking strictly to this position. [\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) Regardless, there was a wide gulf in what parties perceived to be the appropriate punishment to be imposed.

4       Having carefully considered the charges, the facts admitted to by the accused, the submissions of the parties, the various reports and sentencing data put forward in relation to this case, and the authorities and precedent cases that were referred to, I was of the view that a sentence of CT, or the alternative sentence of imprisonment of 57 to 63 months’ imprisonment, sought by the Prosecution was disproportionate and unsupported by authority or precedents. On the flip side, I was also of the view that the proposed sentence of no more than 12 months’ imprisonment proposed by the Defence was manifestly inadequate, and also not in line with the applicable facts and the relevant authorities.

5       Instead, I was of the respectful view that all things considered, an aggregate sentence of 33 months’ imprisonment was fair and proportionate, and would accord with the facts and the relevant legal precedents.

6       The Prosecution and the Defence, both being dissatisfied, have filed appeals against sentence on 4th and 8th November 2022 respectively.

7       While I had made some brief oral remarks when sentencing the accused on 26 October 2022, I now give my full grounds of decision to explain the sentence imposed.

## Antecedents

10     The accused has a host of previous convictions. For the purpose of the present case, his relevant convictions include convictions for the carrying of offensive weapons in public places (sentenced to 3 months’ imprisonment and 6 strokes in 1994), for assault or use of criminal force to deter a public servant from discharge of his duty (sentenced to 2 weeks’ imprisonment in 2008), various drug related convictions and convictions involving the use of intoxicating substances (spanning 1996 to 2013 for which he was sentenced to fines, imprisonment and caning), and a conviction for disorderly behaviour (sentenced in 2012 to a $600 fine). His last conviction was in 2013 for enhanced drug consumption, and he was last released from prison in 2017.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

## Prescribed Punishment

11     For a section 324 offence, the offender shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 7 years, or with fine, or with caning, or with any combination of such punishments.

12     For a section 332 offence, the offender shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 7 years, or with a fine, or with caning, or with any combination of such punishments.

13     For a s 506 offence, the offender shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 2 years, or with fine, or with both; and if the threat is to cause death or grievous hurt, or to cause the destruction of any property by fire, or to cause an offence punishable with death or with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 7 years or more, the offender shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 10 years, or with fine, or with both.

## Prosecution Submissions

### Initial Address on Sentence – calling for a CT report

14     In the Prosecution’s Address on Sentence, DPP Arvindren submitted that a CT pre-sentencing report (“**CT report**”) should be called for, with a view that the accused should be sentenced to a CT term of at least 5 years. I have summarised the main arguments put forward by the Prosecution below.

15     First, the Prosecution argued that the accused was a recalcitrant offender with a long history of drug abuse, substance abuse, property-related offending, as well as violence-related antecedents. He has proven himself to be a habitual offender with blatant disregard for the law. He has now been convicted of four violent offences, with another four violent offences taken into consideration.

16     Second, applying the framework in _Sim Yeow Kee v PP and another appeal_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] 5 SLR 936</span> (“**_Sim Yeow Kee_**”), the Prosecution submitted that it was expedient to impose CT with a view to the accused’s reformation and the prevention of crime. Specifically, as the pre-conditions in s 304(1)(a) of the Criminal Procedure Code (Cap 68, 2012 Rev Ed) ("**CPC**") are satisfied (Stage 1 of the framework), and applying the three steps which make up Stage 2 of the framework, the Prosecution argued that CT was justified due to the following:

> (i)      Step 1: The likely imprisonment term that the accused would have faced is close to 5 years’ imprisonment if he was not sentenced to CT. In this regard, the Prosecution argued that as the accused is a recalcitrant offender with numerous antecedents, in line with the principle of escalation, a longer term of imprisonment is justified. Further, the accused has shown himself to be incapable of refraining from consuming illicit substances, and has become a danger to society due to his addiction issues, as evidenced by his deliberate targeting of strangers without reason, his blatant attack on authority in 2019 and 2022, and his violent behaviour towards his own mother as reflected in the TIC charges. The Prosecution submitted that the accused’s behaviour was due to his self-ingestion of substances, and the offences that he has been convicted of are serious and carry imprisonment terms that range from 7 years to 10 years, with the option of caning. In view of the distinct legal interests protected, this should result in three sentences running consecutively if regular imprisonment should be meted out instead.

> (ii)      Step 2: The Mandatory Aftercare Scheme (“**MAS**”) under Division 5 of the Prisons Act (Cap. 247, 2000 Rev Ed) (“Prisons Act) does not apply to the accused.

> (iii)      Step 3: A sentence of CT would not be unduly disproportionate, given the accused’s likely imprisonment term of close to 5 years, and a longer period of incarceration was required to deter the accused from future offending, particularly in light of his recalcitrant behaviour and history of crime. The Prosecution also argued that the principle of specific deterrence was particularly applicable as the accused has shown a strong propensity to return to his substance addiction. This sentence would also be a signal to the accused about the consequences of his drug/substance abuse.

17     Further, the Prosecution submitted that CT would be more expedient for the accused’s reformation and crime prevention, as its discretionary nature means that the accused would effectively have to prove that he should be released by showing evidence of reform.

18     Having assessed the Prosecution’s arguments, and while the Prosecution did NOT submit specific case authorities or precedents to substantiate its arguments on why the likely imprisonment term that the accused would have faced was close to 5 years’ imprisonment, as the technical requirements of CT were satisfied, and in the interests of expediency since the accused had been in remand for a significant period of time, I agreed to call for a CT report. In the interim, I asked the Prosecution to specifically address me at the next mention, with cases if available, on why it took the position that the imprisonment sentence that would have been imposed was close to the minimum 5-year CT term that it sought. This was clearly an important consideration in light of Step 3 of Stage 2 of the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework that made it clear that a sentence of CT should not be unduly disproportionate, given the offender’s likely imprisonment term.

### Further Address on Sentence

19     A CT report was subsequently produced, which was referred to by the Prosecution in the \`Prosecution’s Further Submissions on Sentence’. In essence, the Prosecution reiterated its position for a sentence of at least 5 years’ CT, based on the following reasons:

> (i)     First, the accused has been found both physical and mentally fit to undergo CT.

> (ii)     Second, based on the report, the accused presents with a high risk of criminal re-offending (with a 70.2% probability of recidivism within 2 years of release). He has also been sentenced to prison multiple times.

> (iii)     Third, the Prosecution highlighted these aspects of the report:

>> a)       The accused’s continued illegal substance use in the future would increase his risk of general and violent reoffending;

>> b)       While his victims suffered only minor injuries despite his use of a weapon, he could potentially inflict more severe injuries when he consumes drugs and experiences hallucinations, should he encounter victims who are elderly or who are less mobile;

>> c)       In the present case, when the voices that the accused heard were too overpowering, he acceded to the voices’ command to take a knife and walk around his neighbourhood, even though he did go to places near his home where he thought there would be no one around, in order not to injure anyone;

>> d)       His mental disorder predisposed him to violence and his illegal drug use would precipitate his violent reoffending; and.

>> e)       The accused’s risk of general and violent reoffending was assessed to be high, and he was predisposed to violent offending due to his substance-induced psychosis and his difficulty in overcoming his drug abuse issues.

> (iv)     Fourth, the Prosecution maintained that the accused’s mental condition should be given no mitigating weight, citing _Public Prosecutor v Mansor bin Ibrahim_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] SGDC 33</span> (“**_Mansor bin Ibrahim_**_”_), and argued that his purported impaired judgment and impulse control was a result of his substance-induced psychosis from voluntary ingestion of substances.

> (v)     Fifth, the Prosecution argued that the accused should be given a structured environment for him: (a) not to relapse into taking unprescribed substances and illegal drugs; and (b) to take proper medication for his issues, citing _Public Prosecutor v Kong Peng Yee_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 2 SLR 295</span> (“**_Kong Peng Yee_**_”_) at \[59\], where the offender with a mental disorder had his sentence enhanced to give him a longer period to continue with his treatment and to provide greater assurance that he would not relapse or cease taking his medication. In the present case, the Prosecution argued that there was no concrete plan and no way to compel the accused to adhere to his self-professed plans to address his condition. Further, the Prosecution took the view that the accused seemed to insinuate that he would possibly relapse into drugs and get into disputes again. In addition, the Prosecution argued that the accused was beyond any family member’s control. Thus, only a structured environment would allow him more time to seek treatment properly. Also, because he has been consuming his medication, he has not been suffering from any auditory hallucination. In essence, the Prosecution’s submission was “…that the accused is someone who, by virtue of his proclivity to crime, must be taken out of circulation.”[^3]

20     As an alternative to the sentence of 5 years’ CT, the Prosecution submitted for a global imprisonment term of 57 to 63 months. This global sentence consisted of running three sentences consecutively for offences committed against three different victims, and where the offences concerned three distinct underlying legal interests. These comprised sentences for the following offences:

> (i)     Section 324 of the Penal Code (causing grievous hurt),

> (ii)     Section 332 of the Penal Code (causing hurt to a public servant); and

> (iii)     One sentence under section 506 of the Penal Code (criminal intimidation).

21     For the section 324 offence (DAC-902442-2022), the Prosecution argued that it had derived its sentence based on the process in _Ng Soon Kim v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] SGHC 247</span> (“**_Ng Soon Kim_**”) as follows:

> (i)     Based on the first and second stage of the process, the initial indication was for 12 months’ imprisonment to be imposed as the weapon was concealed and extremely dangerous. The harm was also not minor as the victim required right hand debridement surgery and there was potential harm to innocent members of the public. The Prosecution further submitted for “a substantial uplift of 24-30 months at Stage 3, to protect the public from a person who is an absolute menace when he consumes illegal substances and drugs. Specific deterrence and prevention features here as well, to signal to the accused the consequences of his drug consumption. This will also include an enhanced sentence of 3 months’ in lieu of caning. The eventual sentencing position for this offence will be **36-42 months**.” [\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4)

> (ii)     Further, the Prosecution highlighted that the decision in _Ng Soon Kim_ emphasises that the focus should be on culpability rather than harm for section 324 offences, and that for offences under section 324 of the Penal Code, there were no benchmarks provided for each step. Instead, it has to be considered that the accused’s attack was an intentional attack on a random member of public, and the TIC charges should also be taken into account here.

22     For the criminal intimidation offences under section 506 of the Penal Code (DAC-902443-2022 and DAC-905090-2022), the Prosecution submitted that at least 18 months’ imprisonment was warranted per offence, emphasising that the maximum punishment for such offences is 10 years’ imprisonment. The Prosecution also stated the following:

> (i)     In _Tan Kay Beng v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2006\] 4 SLR 10</span> (“**_Tan Kay Beng_**”), it was highlighted to the Court at \[45\] that “A threat to cause death falls within the second limb. Where the threat to kill is without a weapon, the sentencing range for offenders with no prior record is between six to 12 months’ imprisonment. Where a weapon was used as part of the threat to cause death, a term of two years’ imprisonment was imposed by the High Court in two recent cases.” However, the Prosecution agreed that the Court in _Tan Kay Beng_ emphasized that the factual matrix remains paramount.

> (ii)     On the facts of the present case, even though the accused did not utter any threatening words, he had committed criminal intimidation against a taxi driver followed shortly by targeting a police officer right outside a police division. The latter attack against authority, after a substance-induced episode, had also taken place not long after his earlier offences of violence against random members of the public. His crime spree only came to an end after he was shot and arrested.

23     Finally, for the 2019 section 332 offence (DAC-908158-2022), relying on _Public Prosecutor v Yeo Ek Boon Jeffrey_ and another matter <span class="citation">\[2018\] 3 SLR 1080</span> (“**_Jeffrey Yeo_**”), the Prosecution submitted for at least 3 months imprisonment based on the following:

> (i)     The officer was attacked right at the entrance of a police station;

> (ii)     The attack was on a vulnerable part of the victim’s body (his jaw); and

> (iii)     The victim was attacked merely because he had asked the accused to wait awhile, while other officers were activated.

24     For the global sentence, the Prosecution submitted that three sentences should run consecutively, namely, the sentences for the section 324 offence, the section 332 offence, and for one of the section 506 offences. The Prosecution argued that this approach was in line with the totality principle, and that such a global sentence would not be crushing on the accused. Further, these three sentences concerned offences committed against three different victims, and involved three distinct underlying legal interests. Hence, running them consecutively would not offend the one-transaction principle. Thus, the global sentence would be at least 57 to 63 months’ imprisonment.

## Mitigation Plea

25     The Defence objected to the calling of a CT report, arguing that there was no basis for the imposition of CT. Even after the CT report was called for and received, the Defence maintained its position that CT was not appropriate. I have summarised the Defence’s arguments below.

### Initial Mitigation Plea – Objection to the calling of a CT report

26     The Defence submitted that based on the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework, this “is plainly an inappropriate case for CT to be imposed”, as “…it would not be expedient to sentence the Accused to CT”. The Defence argued as follows:

> (i)     First, the Prosecution’s submission that the likely imprisonment term would be “more than close to 5 years’ imprisonment”[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5) was unsupported by any precedent.

> (ii)     Second, while the accused would not qualify for the MAS, this factor was not decisive, citing _Public Prosecutor v Ong Say Kiat_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 5 SLR 946</span> (“**_Ong Say Kiat_**”), where it was made clear that this was just one of the factors to be considered under the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework.

> (iii)     Third, a sentence of CT was unduly disproportionate.

27     The Defence further argued that an alternative sentence of not more than 1 year’s imprisonment would serve as a fair and just global sentence in the present case. This global sentence was arrived at as follows:[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6)

28     Concerning its proposed imprisonment terms for each of the offences, the Defence submitted that they were justified based on precedents and various other factors. I elaborate on the Defence’s arguments below.

##### The s 332 offence (DAC-908158-2022)

29     The Defence submitted that the sentencing framework set out by the High Court in _Jeffrey Yeo_ for section 332 offences should apply. This consisted of three broad sentencing bands based on the twin considerations of harm and culpability, where the principle of escalation is specifically contemplated in this framework, and which takes into account the offender’s criminal history and propensity. The Defence submitted that the present offence falls squarely within the lower end of Category 1 of the _Jeffrey Yeo_ framework, and that his sentence should not exceed three months’ imprisonment on the facts. The Defence also made reference to the list of non-exhaustive factors set out in _Jeffrey Yeo_ at \[60\], and highlighted the following.

> (i)     First, with respect to the degree of hurt caused and its consequences, this was minor as the victim suffered from tenderness and swelling of his left temporoparietal region, and was discharged with medication and 2 days medical leave certification.[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7)

> (ii)     Second, there was no use or attempted use of a weapon or dangerous implement or means to do harm, as the accused only used his fist to punch the victim.

> (iii)     Third, there was a significant contributory link between the accused’s drug-induced psychosis and this incident, though he was not of unsound mind.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8)

> (iv)     Fourth, the accused did not plan or premeditate his assault on the victim. Neither did he do so in the context of resisting arrest nor demonstrating his contempt for authority. Rather, it was out of fear and desperation that the accused committed the offence, as he had hit the victim with his fist so that he would be arrested and charged, and therefore be safe from his perceived enemies whom he thought were trying to kill him. The accused did not intend to inflict more serious harm than what materialised, and he was in the throes of his psychosis at the time.

> (v)     Fifth, the accused was the only offender involved, and this was not a sustained or repeated attack.

> (vi)     Lastly, while the accused has an antecedent of assault or use of criminal force to deter a public servant from discharge of his duty, this occurred in 2008 and is dated. That earlier offence could not have been serious, bearing in mind that his imprisonment term for that 2008 antecedent was (only) two weeks’ imprisonment.

##### The s 324 offence (DAC-902442-2022)

30     For this offence, the Defence submitted for a sentence of not more than 9 months’ imprisonment “in the worst case”, based on the application of the 3-step approach in _Ng Soon Kim._

31     As regards the first step, this involved considering what was the appropriate sentence for a first-time offender who pleaded guilty, on the assumption that the hurt caused was the subject of a charge under section 323.

> (i)     In this regard, Defence highlighted that the injury suffered by the victim, Wong, on 17 February 2022 was a minor laceration to a non-vulnerable part of the body, which fell squarely in Band 1 of the first step of the _Ng Soon Kim_ framework. Specifically, it was a single laceration on the back of his right hand in the region under his little finger, and there was no permanent disability or substantial impairment. About 2 weeks after the incident, the wound had healed, and Wong had recovered to the extent that he had full active range of motion of his fingers such that he was given an open date with no active follow up plans. Under Section 323, the indicative starting sentence would be a fine, or a short custodial term up to 4 weeks.

> (ii)     Further, citing _PP v Zhai Huilu_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGDC 84</span> (“**_Zhai Huilu_**”), where a single deep laceration on the victim’s right upper lip attracted a starting sentence of 1 month’s imprisonment at the first step of the _Ng Soon Kim_ framework, and adjusting downwards to take into consideration that the hand injury to Wong in the present case involved a less vulnerable part of the body, and also as the laceration was not deep, the indicative starting imprisonment here would be 2 to 3 weeks.

32     As regards the second step of the _Ng Soon Kim_ framework, this involves considering a suitable uplift to the tentative s 323 sentence having regard to the dangerous means used. The Defence argued that the suitable uplift would be approximately 7 to 8 months, having regard to the following factors:

> (i)     A knife was used, and this was swung at the general direction of Wong’s head.

> (ii)     The offence took place in public along a pavement.

> (iii)     Wong was an unsuspecting stranger.

> (iv)     However, the potential harm was ultimately limited by the fact that the accused was suffering from a limp owing to a history of bilateral foot fractures and a sensory stroke,[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9) and he was thus physically incapable of chasing or causing further harm to Wong.

33     As regards the third step of the process, which involves calibrating the sentence to what was appropriate having considered the particular aggravating or mitigating circumstances, the Defence highlighted the following:

> (i)     While the accused was not a first offender, most of his antecedents are drug-related, and even his antecedents involving violence are dated and, from the sentences he received for those offences, they were not particularly egregious or aggravating. The sentences were imprisonment of 2 weeks for assaulting or using criminal force to deter a public servant from the discharge of his duty in 2008; and a fine of $1,000 in default of 5 days’ imprisonment for mischief in 2012 (with a charge of voluntarily causing hurt taken into consideration). These antecedents do not justify the drastic uplift that the Prosecution had sought.

> (ii)     Next, the accused’s psychiatric report from the IMH dated 10 March 2022 (“**March 2022 IMH Report**”) made it clear that the accused was suffering from substance-induced psychosis, and there was clear evidence that he was actively psychotic and that his hallucinations and persecutory delusions would have contributed substantially to the alleged offences by impairing his judgment and impulse control.[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10) In this regard, the Defence argued that the existence of a mental disorder on the part of the offender is always a relevant factor in the sentencing process (citing _Public Prosecutor v Chong Hou En_ <span class="citation">\[2015\] 3 SLR 222</span> (“**_Chong Hou En_**”) at \[24\]). In the present case, based on the psychiatric evidence, the accused’s judgment and impulse control were impaired by his psychosis.

> (iii)     Further, after this incident, the accused had taken a taxi to the police station, where he intended to surrender himself.[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11)

> (iv)     Finally, the accused was pleading guilty. As held in _Ng Soon Kim_, even if the evidence against an accused was largely uncontroverted, a timeous plea of guilty saves precious judicial time and resources that would otherwise have been incurred at trial.

34     The Defence further submitted that if the court took the view that the _Ng Soon Kim_ framework should not apply, a sentence of 9 months’ imprisonment was also supported by precedent citing, in particular, the decision in _Zhai Huilu_, where the offender, who was a first offender, was convicted of a section 324 offence after a nine-day trial, and was finally sentenced to 5 months’ imprisonment by the appellate court.

##### The first section 506 offence (DAC-905090-2022)

35     For this offence, which involved criminal intimidation of the taxi driver, Goh, at or about 8.45pm, the Defence highlighted that this incident took place after the occurrence of the section 324 offence, when the accused had resolved to surrender himself to the police. He had thus taken Goh’s taxi to Clementi Police Division for this purpose. As the taxi was nearing Clementi Police Division, the accused attempted to alight while the taxi was still in motion, causing him to fall and lay on the ground. When Goh went to check on him, the accused pointed the knife towards Goh and charged at Goh, notwithstanding his limp. Goh ran away, and the accused stopped charging at Goh and walked towards Clementi Police Division. Goh subsequently got back into his taxi and locked the door, at which point the accused pointed at him from outside the locked taxi.

36     The Defence submitted that based on the following precedents, the appropriate sentence per charge would not be more than 2 months’ imprisonment:

> (i)     In _Public Prosecutor v Tay Hai Choon_ <span class="citation">\[2009\] SGDC 270</span> (“**_Tay Hai Choon_**”), the accused claimed trial and was convicted, _inter alia_, on a section 506 charge (second limb). There, the accused ran and charged at the victim with a crowbar, stabbing and swinging the crowbar at the victim multiple times, while saying to the victim, “_you bastard I want to kill you_”. The victim tried frantically to avoid the accused, and the crowbar missed him narrowly many times. The accused chased after the victim as he tried to escape, and would have hit the victim had his crowbar not missed the victim and hit a lamppost instead. The accused was sentenced to 6 months’ imprisonment. While both _Tay Hai Choon_ and the present case concerned offenders who charged at a victim with a dangerous weapon, the Defence submitted that _Tay Hai Choon_ was more serious as the offender’s use of dangerous weapon there was accompanied by a death threat, which was absent here. Also, in _Tay Hai Choon_, the offender had stabbed and swung the crowbar at the victim many times, in a close enough vicinity that the crowbar missed the victim many times, and the offender had also chased after the victim multiple times. In the present case, there was no evidence that the accused came close to hitting Goh, or that Goh had to dodge the accused’s blows. Moreover, after Goh ran away, the accused stopped charging at Goh and walked towards Clementi Police Division.[^12] Finally, the offender in _Tay Hai Choon_ had claimed trial, while the accused was pleading guilty in the present case. Counsel submitted that adjusting the 6 months’ imprisonment sentence in _Tay Hai Choon_ downwards, and thereafter taking into account the public disquiet the offence caused, the fact that Goh was a stranger to the accused, as well as the accused’s antecedents, 2 months’ imprisonment was fair and just.

> (ii)     In _Public Prosecutor v Ong Sock Hung_ <span class="citation">\[2005\] SGDC 57</span> (“**_Ong Sock Hung_**_”)_, the accused claimed trial to a single charge under section 506 (first limb), for brandishing a chopper outside the victim’s flat, making a hacking motion and saying “_I will kill your whole family_”. The accused was sentenced to 2 months’ imprisonment.

> (iii)     In _Lwee Kwi Ling Mary v Quek Chin Huat_ <span class="citation">\[2003\] 2 SLR(R) 145</span>(“**_Lwee Kwi Ling Mary_**”), the accused claimed trial to, _inter alia_, one charge of criminal intimidation (first limb) for threatening to kill the respondent while wielding a chopper. She was sentenced on appeal to 3 months’ imprisonment.

37     The Defence submitted that bearing in mind that the accused’s wielding of the knife in the present case was not accompanied by any threat to kill Goh, a sentence of 2 months’ imprisonment was supported by the above precedents.

##### The second section 506 offence (DAC-902443-2022)

38     This offence involved criminal intimidation of the police officer, Tan, at or about 8.55pm. It occurred shortly after the first criminal intimidation offence, when the accused walked away from Goh towards Clementi Police Division. The accused had walked towards three of the police officers, including Tan, who were on duty at the entrance of Clementi Police Division. The police officers there had commanded him to stop and to drop the knife, while pointing their guns at him. At this point, the accused suddenly charged towards Tan with his knife in hand. Counsel stated that the accused was heavily suffering under his psychosis, and desired to be killed by a gunshot so that he would no longer suffer. Tan had fired a live round that struck the accused’s left arm, after which he fell to the round and was immobilised by more than 6 police officers.

39     The Defence submitted that while this event caused some public disquiet, there was no realistic prospect that the accused would have been able to make good on his threat of grievous hurt, as he was a solo person armed with a knife faced with at least three police officers with guns. The Defence submitted that the appropriate sentence for this offence would be not more than 2 months’ imprisonment.

##### Global sentence

40     Bearing in mind the totality principle, and the one-transaction rule, counsel submitted that it would be appropriate that the imprisonment sentences for the section 324 offence and the section 332 offence to be made to run consecutively, while the sentences for the two section 506 offences should run concurrently, since the section 324 offence, and the two section 506 offences occurred over the course of an hour, and the same specific aggravating factors would have already been taken into account. This would take the global sentence to not more than 1 year’s imprisonment as follows:

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="1"><colgroup><col width="50.46%"><col width="49.54%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Charge</b></p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Imprisonment sentence</b></p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">The Section 332 offence</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Not more than 3 months</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">The Section 324 offence</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Not more than 9 months</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">The first Section 506 offence (for Goh)</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Not more than 2 months (concurrent)</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">The second Section 506 offence (for Tan)</p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Not more than 2 months (concurrent)</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Global imprisonment sentence</b></p></td><td align="left" class="" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1"><b>Not more than 1 year</b></p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

41     Further, even if the court should decide to have more than two sentences run consecutively, this would take the imprisonment sentence to the vicinity of 1 year 2 months, which was nowhere close to the sentence of “_close to 5 years’ imprisonment_” that the Prosecution was seeking. Counsel also argued that in the circumstances, the minimum CT sentence of 5 years would represent an uplift of around 4 years on top of the accused’s sentence, and this would be plainly and manifestly excessive.

42     Separately, counsel also argued while the applicability of the MAS (Step 2 of Stage 2 of the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework) would be a factor militating against CT, the fact that the MAS was not applicable here should be a neutral factor, and not to be counted against the accused.

43     Further, counsel reiterated that CT would be disproportionate in light of the likely imprisonment sentences, and also bearing in mind the following cases:

> (i)     In _Public Prosecutor v Ibrahim bin Bajuri_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGDC 89</span> (“**_Ibrahim bin Bajuri_**”), the court decided that to impose the minimum term of 5 years’ CT on an offender who would have been sentenced to 33 months and 72 days’ imprisonment would have been unduly disproportionate.

> (ii)     In _Public Prosecutor v Joseph Doray s/o Saverymuthu_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] SGDC 60</span> (“**_Joseph Doray s/o Saverymuthu_**”), the court also found that to impose the minimum term of 5 years’ CT on an offender who would have been sentenced to 4 years’ imprisonment would have been unduly disproportionate.

44     Counsel also argued that aside from the fact that the sheer disproportionality of a sentence of CT would in and of itself dispose of the argument for CT, there were additional compelling reasons against a sentence of CT. These were as follows:

> (i)     While the accused was a habitual drug offender, with convictions for consumption of morphine and diamorphine from the 1990s, since his release from LT2 imprisonment in the late 2010s, he has tried as much as possible to steer clear of Class A drugs. His consumption of cough medicine, which led to the offences in question was, in some way, demonstrative of his own efforts of de-escalation. The accused was appalled at his actions and was deeply remorseful, and determined that this is where the buck stops.

> (ii)     He continues to receive familial support, and is visited once a month by his mother and sister.

> (iii)     As far as the prevention of crime is concerned, the accused is physically less of a danger to society than before he committed the offences, due to the after effects of the gunshot wound to his left arm such that he longer has a full range of motion or strength in that arm. Coupled with his bilateral foot fractures that caused a discernible limp and his advancing age, he is in constant pain and does not regard himself as physically capable of committing the same offences again.

45     In summary, counsel reiterated against the court calling for a CT report, particularly when considering that any imprisonment sentence would be substantially lower than the minimum CT term of five years, and sought a sentence of not more than 1 year’s imprisonment instead.

### Further Mitigation Plea

46     Subsequently, after receipt of the CT report, the Defence tendered a further plea in mitigation, reiterating its position that this is not an appropriate case for CT. Amongst other things, the Defence assailed the Prosecution for apparently taking the position that it was “…_prepared_ to address the Court on the imprisonment term that should be imposed _if_ the Court is not inclined to impose CT”, noting that such an approach would be inconsistent with the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework, which requires the court to first consider, as part of Step 1 of Stage 2, the imprisonment term that would likely apply to the offender in the circumstances of the case. This should be done before it turns to consider whether it is expedient to impose CT instead. The Defence also pointed out that consideration of the likely imprisonment term was also a necessary pre-condition before the court could consider whether a sentence of CT would be unduly disproportionate, which was Step 3 of Stage 2 of the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13)

47     Further, the Defence reiterated its position that CT would be disproportionate to the likely imprisonment sentences in the present case, and also argued that the Prosecution’s belated position that 57 to 63 months’ imprisonment would have been imposed, had imprisonment been considered, was unsupported by case precedents. Specifically, the Defence pointed out that “…(t)he sentences that the Prosecution seeks for the Section 324 and Section 506 would be one of the harshest sentences ever imposed for Section 324 and 506 offences since the Sentencing Information Repository (“**SIR**”) started collecting data on 22 October 2001”. [\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14)

48     The Defence also elaborated on why the Prosecution’s assessment of the sentences for the individual offences was unsupportable.

49     As regards the section 324 offence, the Defence argued against the Prosecution’s proposed 36 to 42 months’ imprisonment. This sentence was arrived at through the Prosecution:(1) coming up with an indicative sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment; (2) adding to this an uplift of 24-30 months imprisonment at the third stage of the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework, which includes an additional three months’ imprisonment in lieu of caning. The Defence criticised the Prosecution’s approach as follows:

> (i)     The Defence pointed out that “(t)his will be, without exaggeration, one of the harshest sentences **ever** imposed by any court for a Section 324 offence,” as the sentence the Prosecution is submitting for is in the **99****th****percentile** of sentences for section 324 offences according to the SIR data on sentences for section 324 offences passed since 22 October 2001;

> (ii)     Such an extraordinary sentence requires extraordinary justification, particularly when considering that the _actual_ harm inflicted was a single laceration on the back of the victim’s right hand in the region under his little finger, with no permanent disability or substantial impairment, and full recovery in two weeks;[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15) and

> (iii)     The Prosecution has cited no precedent in support of its sentencing position for such a sentence, and the Defence’s submissions on sentence has been left unrebutted. In particular, there was nothing to justify the uplift of 24-30 months’ imprisonment at the third stage of the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework.

50     As regards the section 506 offences, for which the Prosecution had proposed a sentence of at least 18 months’ imprisonment each, the Prosecution had based its assessment on the decision in _Tan Kay Beng_, and on the fact that the maximum imprisonment punishment for the offence is 10 years. Thus, the Prosecution had argued that the 18 months’ imprisonment they sought was less than 1/5 of the maximum sentence. The Defence criticised this position of the Prosecution as follows:

> (i)     It was inappropriate for the Prosecution to simply rely on the statutory maximum sentence to support its desired sentence. Instead, the appropriate sentence should be meted out bearing in mind the relevant sentencing considerations as well as all the relevant factors in each case, along with past sentences that have been imposed for similar cases.

> (ii)     The SIR data showed that the sentence of 18 months’ imprisonment sought by the Prosecution was again unprecedented for the present facts, bearing in mind that of the 1,230 charges of section 506 (both first and second limbs) prosecuted since 22 October 2001, there were only **12** cases of criminal intimidation with a sentence harsher than what the Prosecution was seeking, and the sentence sought by the Prosecution was in the **99****th****percentile** of sentences for Section 506 offences imposed by any court.

> (iii)     The Prosecution has cited no precedent to support its harsh sentence because it could not do so. Even the case of _Tan Kay Beng_ cited in its \`Further Submissions on Sentence’ dealt with a threat to cause death, rather than one to cause grievous hurt as in the present case.

> (iv)     The Prosecution has not distinguished or rebutted any of the three precedents cited by the Defence in its initial Mitigation Plea, all of which were claimed trial cases and which involved the use by the offender of weapons (crowbar and/or chopper) in the course of making threats to cause death to the victims, namely the cases of _Tay Hai Choon_ (where the offender was sentenced to 6 months’ imprisonment); _Ong Sock Hung_ (where the offender was sentenced to 2 months’ imprisonment); and _Lwee Kwi Ling Mary_ (where the offender was sentenced to 3 months’ imprisonment).

51     As for the proposed sentence for the section 332 offence, the Defence made no further submissions as both parties were aligned on the proposed sentence of 3 months’ imprisonment for this offence.

52     As for the global sentence, the Defence took issue with the Prosecution’s proposal for three of the sentences to run consecutively, and pointed out that: “Having already submitted for one of the harshest ever sentences for the Section 324 and 506 offences, the Prosecution further seek for three sentences to be run consecutively. The sentence they seek is the very definition of the crushing sentence that the High Court in _Shouffee_ cautioned against”.

53     The Defence reiterated that CT would not be appropriate since even the lowest CT sentence would be unduly disproportionate, and argued that the accused “…is not an individual who is beyond hope, and certainly not an offender who is deserving of one of the harshest sentences ever imposed by the courts, in respect of the Section 324 and 506 offences.” Further, the Defence pointed out that:

> (i)     At page 8 of the CT report, it was stated that the accused has a supportive family (mother and sister) that provides him with emotional and practical support and that “(t)he presence of support from his family and his motivation to keep himself well would help to mitigate his risk of reoffending.” Further, while the accused’s mother does have a PPO against him, the CT Report emphasises that she wishes to revoke it.[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

> (ii)     It was also clear from the CT Report that the accused has insight into his condition and has taken steps to live with it and to seek help if necessary, including deliberately go to places near his home where no one would be around when the voices in his head were overpowering. He would also admit himself to IMH when his conditions worsened.23 Further, even in a state of psychosis, the accused demonstrated a cognisance for authority. As mentioned at \[4\] of the SOF, the accused called the police on himself on the night of the offences, and also took the taxi to the police station because he wanted to turn himself in and be stopped.[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17) Similarly, with respect to his section 332 offence, the accused committed the offence because he wanted to be arrested, as he was under the impression that he needed to go back into lockup as there were people outside who wanted to kill him.[^18] The CT Report also described the accused’s disbelief and fear when he watched the footage of him attacking others, as well as his deep remorse, and his plans to admit himself to IMH if his symptoms worsen in the future.[^19]

> (iii)     The CT Report also corroborated the Defence’s submission that the accused is physically less of a danger to society than before he committed the offence.[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20)

54     Finally, the Defence argued that the accused’s substance-induced psychosis, consisting of auditory and command hallucinations, involved an underlying condition, where his abuse of cough syrup resulted in the hallucination becoming active. Thus, the Defence submitted that at least _some_ mitigating weight should be given to the accused’s substance-induced psychosis, to account for the extent to which it may be attributed to his underlying condition. Further, even if not considered a mitigating factor, it should not be an aggravating factor, especially since the accused’s consumption of cough syrup and diazepam has not resulted in charges have been tendered against the accused for illicit drug consumption. In any event, even if the court should regard a longer term of imprisonment to be necessary to ensure the accused’s compliance with his medication regime and to provide him with a controlled environment, it does not justify the crushing sentence of CT, or 57 to 63 months’ imprisonment that the Prosecution was seeking.

## The Court’s decision on Sentence

55     At the initial mention of the case before me on 27 September 2022, I had asked the Prosecution to explain its views on the likely imprisonment sentences for the each of the offences, such as to justify why a sentence of CT would not be considered disproportionate under the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework. This was something which the Prosecution had failed to do in its initial submissions on sentence.

56     I also sought views from parties on the mental condition of the accused, in relation to the self-induced psychosis that preceded his commission of the offences, and how this might impact on sentence. In addition, I asked parties to address me on the appropriateness of a longer custodial term to ensure that the accused take his medication to address his condition. I appreciate the efforts of parties to deal with these matters by the second mention on 26 October 2022.

57     Having carefully considered the arguments of parties, which I have attempted to accurately and comprehensively set out in these Grounds of Decision, as well as having examined the documents and information made available to me, including the CT report, the SOF and its annexures consisting of medical and IMH reports, the SIR data provided by the Defence, and the various case authorities, I am of the view that, all things considered, a global sentence of 33 months’ imprisonment is the appropriate sentence. This sentence is, of course, quite dissimilar to the sentence of CT of 5 years, or the imprisonment terms proposed by the Defence (and the Prosecution).

58     To explain how I reached my decision on the sentence to impose, I start off by discussing the seminar judgement on CT, namely the decision of the three-judge panel of the High Court in _Sim Yeow Kee_, a case which laid down clear guidelines pertaining to the imposition of CT as a punishment.

## The _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework

59     In _Sim Yeow Kee_, the High Court set out a 2-stage framework to be adopted when considering cases involving the possible imposition of CT. This framework is as follows:

> (i)     Stage 1 – The court has to be satisfied that the "technical" requirements set out in s 304(1) of the CPC for imposing CT are met (see \[86\]).

> (ii)     Stage 2 – The court has to be satisfied that it is "expedient" to sentence the offender to CT with a view to his reformation _and_ the prevention of crime (see \[87\]). This involves going through the following three steps:

>> a)       Step 1: The likely imprisonment term which would be imposed for the instant offence, taking into account the following (see \[99\]):

>>> (A)       The escalation principle which justifies imposing a longer sentence on a persistent offender in view of his antecedents.

>>> (B)       The court’s power to run more than two sentences consecutively where the offender faces 3 or more proceeded charges. This would be especially relevant in the case of a persistent or habitual offender, where there are extraordinary cumulative aggravating factors, or where there is a particular public interest.

>> b)       Step 2: Whether the MAS would apply to the offender if he were sentenced to a term of imprisonment. If the MAS is applicable and if the court is of the view that it would benefit the offender, these factors could cumulatively militate against the imposition of a sentence of CT (see \[102\]).

>> c)       Step 3: Whether a sentence of CT will be unduly disproportionate as compared to the aggregate imprisonment which is likely to be imposed (see \[105\]).

60     Applying the above framework to the two appellants involved in _Sim Yeow Kee_, the Court decided that:

> (i)     In the case of the first appellant (Sim), even if the Court ran all three imprisonment sentences consecutively, his sentence would only be 42 months’ imprisonment. Sim also qualified for the MAS. In light of these considerations, a sentence of CT would be unduly disproportionate and the Court imposed a sentence of 42 months’ imprisonment instead (see \[110\] – \[114\]).

> (ii)     In the case of the second appellant (Loi), the Court decided that Loi, a habitual offender, would have been sentenced to a global sentence of 78 months’ imprisonment (with four sentences running consecutively). Loi was also eligible for MAS. The Court also said that it would have been prepared to find that _at least_ six years’ CT should have been imposed on Loi because of the extent of his criminal record and the evident need for him to be specifically deterred. However, the Court ultimately declined to disturb the term of five years’ CT imposed by the District Judge as the Prosecution had not appealed the sentence (see \[116\] – \[118\]).

61     In the present case, the Defence made it clear that in determining whether a sentence of CT was appropriate, this has to be determined by applying the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework, in particular, by determining with the sentence of CT would be unduly disproportionate to the likely imprisonment sentence that would be imposed. I agreed with the Defence.

62     As regards the framework itself, since there was no dispute that the technical requirement for CT applied i.e. that Stage 1 of the framework was satisfied, I will move on and proceed to discuss the application of the three-steps that constitute Stage 2 of the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework.

### Sentence for the s 332 offence: Applying Jeffrey Yeo

65     It can be seen from the above table that both the Prosecution and the Defence broadly agreed that a sentence of 3 months’ imprisonment was an appropriate sentence for the s 332 offence committed in 2019. This was primarily based on the decision in _Jeffrey Yeo_, with the Prosecution highlighting several factors as being relevant to sentence, _viz_, the fact that the officer was attacked right at the entrance of a police station; the attack was on a vulnerable part of the victim’s body; and the fact that the victim was attacked merely because he had asked the accused to wait while other officers were activated.

66     As for the Defence, similarly citing _Jeffrey Yeo_, essentially the same sentence of 3 months’ imprisonment was arrived at with the Defence highlighting several features, including the minor injuries suffered by the victim; the fact that the hurt was caused with only the accused’s fist rather than with a weapon or any dangerous implement or means; the contributory link between the accused’s drug-induced psychosis and this incident; the lack of planning or premeditation; the fact that this was not a sustained or repeated attack, and also the fact that his sole similar antecedent was relatively dated and had only resulted in a sentence of two weeks’ imprisonment.

67     In my oral remarks delivered on 26 October 2022, I noted that the offence was committed after the accused had abused cough syrup without prescription. Among other things, in the IMH reports dated 12 July 2019 and 12 December 2019 (both included as annexures to the SOF), the psychiatrists who evaluated the accused in 2019 had stated, _inter alia_, that the accused was diagnosed with drug induced psychosis from the cough mixture that he was abusing. This was following the assault on the victim on 9 June 2019.

68     I also noted that even before the commission of this offence on 9 June 2019, the accused had a total of five admissions to IMH of which four were in May and June 2019. Indeed, during the 4 to 6 June 2019 admission, he was diagnosed with drug induced psychosis. On 10 June 2019, after the assault, the accused was admitted to IMH with reported auditory hallucinations and persecutory delusions. His sister reported that he was non adherent to treatment as his medication was found untouched. The accused also admitted to taking cough syrup and was diagnosed with drug-induced psychosis. The report dated 12 December 2019 concluded, _inter alia_, that "…he would benefit significantly from adherence to medication, abstinence from substances and continued follow up with his treating team"

69     Thus, what was significant was that even before the 332 offence, the accused was supposed to take medication for his condition. Certainly, he was not supposed to consume any substance that triggers his condition. Instead, on the facts, he had taken cough syrup, resulting in drug induced psychosis. This was the background behind the first assault.

70     In light of the circumstances of the offence, I broadly agreed with the parties, in particularly with the Prosecution, that in line with the _Jeffrey Yeo_ framework, a sentence of at least 3 months’ imprisonment was necessary. That said, I also accepted that this offence involved a relatively minor injury caused where the accused had punched the victim three times on his face. While the accused has a previous similar offence in 2008 for which he was sentenced to two weeks’ imprisonment, I agreed with the Defence that this offence was relatively dated and apparently relatively minor. All things considered, I agreed that the proposed sentence of three months’ imprisonment for the present s 332 offence was an appropriate punishment, and a sufficient uplift from the earlier imprisonment term of two weeks’ imprisonment imposed on him in 2008.

71     I would add that the issue of the drug-induced psychosis, which I have made mention above, would feature even more prominently later in 2022, and cause even greater concern, as it was against that backdrop that the accused committed a host of new offences of a more serious nature. Those offences led to the framing of more charges, three of which were proceeded with before me, and two were taken into consideration for sentencing. It is to these three proceeded charges for offences committed in 2022 that I now turn to.

### Sentence for the s 324 offence

72     Section 324 provides that voluntarily causing hurt by dangerous weapons or means is punishable with imprisonment for a term that may extend to seven years, or with fine or caning or any combination of such punishments. The dangerous weapons or means stipulated by s 324 include any instrument for shooting, stabbing or cutting, any instrument which, used as a weapon of offence, is likely to cause death, any fire or any heated substance etc.

73     In the present case, unlike for the s 332 offence where there was a broad consensus between parties that the likely imprisonment sentence should be about 3 months’ imprisonment, the Prosecution and Defence were poles apart on what the likely imprisonment term for the s 324 offence should be.

74     The Prosecution submitted that the likely sentence should be 36 to 42 months’ imprisonment, while the Defence took the position that the sentence should be no more than 9 months’ imprisonment. These diametrically divergent views were taken despite both sides agreeing that the sentence should be based on the decision of Menon CJ in _Ng Soon Kim_. It was thus clear that a thorough examination of _Ng Soon Kim_ was necessary before a proper determination of an appropriate sentence for this offence could be made.

#### The decision in Ng Soon Kim

75      _Ng Soon Kim_ concerned an appellant, a taxi driver, who pleaded guilty to a charge of voluntarily causing hurt by means of fire under s 324 of the Penal Code. His victim was another taxi driver. In the court below, the appellant was sentenced to 14 months’ imprisonment and disqualified from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for 18 months. On appeal against his sentence, Menon CJ set aside the sentence of 14 months’ imprisonment and imposed a sentence of seven months’ imprisonment in its place. He also reduced the disqualification term to nine months. In coming to his decision, his Honour gave the following guidance on sentencing for s 324 offences:

> (i)     Section 324 is the aggravated form of the offence prescribed under s 323, but under s 324, the identical harm would be liable to the imposition of the much heftier penalties prescribed where dangerous means were used. This made it clear that the emphasis on harm and culpability could not be identical (see \[9\]).

> (ii)     Section 324 sets out various specific means for the infliction of hurt, some of which are likely to be inherently more egregious than others, and much would depend on the facts. A sentencing framework could not be prescribed for s 324 offences, as the jurisprudence dealing with sentencing under s 324 was not sufficient at this stage (see \[11).

> (iii)     A three-step process would be adopted to arrive at an appropriate sentence for an offence under s 324 (see \[12\]).

>> a)       First, the court would consider what an appropriate sentence would be had the hurt alone been the subject of an offence under s 323.

>> b)       Second, the court would consider the application of a suitable uplift, having regard to the dangerous means used, including the potential harm that could result from the chosen means of offending.

>> c)       Finally, the sentence would be calibrated having regard to the particular aggravating or mitigating circumstances.

##### First Step: Sentence under s 323

76     As regards the first step of the process, namely, determining the sentence if the hurt alone been the subject of an offence under s 323, this is achieved through the application of the sentencing framework in _Low Song Chye v Public Prosecutor and another appeal_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] SGHC 140</span> (“**_Low Song Chye_**”). This framework, set out below, applies for a first-time offender who pleads guilty.

four weeks to six months’ imprisonment</p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">3</p></td><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Serious harm: serious injuries which are permanent in nature and/or which necessitate significant surgical procedures</p></td><td align="left"
