In _Ng Soon Kim_, Menon CJ also considered the fact that the appellant had deliberately targeted the victim’s face, which was a vulnerable part of his body, and the fact that the offence had taken place in a road rage setting, as aggravating factors. Thus, despite deciding that the harm was low,[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21) Menon CJ determined that a short custodial term of two months would have been justified had the hurt alone been the subject of a charge brought under s 323 (see \[14\]).

##### Second Step: Applying a suitable uplift based on the dangerous means used

77     As regards the second step, this involves applying a suitable uplift based on the dangerous means used to inflict the injuries. It requires a consideration of the actual harm caused, the potential for harm, and also a consideration of possible public alarm. In _Ng Soon Kim_, Menon CJ decided that he would have imposed an uplift of around six months’ imprisonment due to the alarm caused to a third party (including the victim’s passenger), the potential for more harm if some part of the vehicle’s interior had caught fire as a result of the means used, as well as the public alarm caused by the fact that the offence had taken place in in the middle of a busy road intersection (see \[16\]).

##### Third Step: Calibrating on account of other considerations

78     This step involves considering the various aggravating and mitigating circumstances, including the plea of guilt with the resulting savings in judicial time and resources, as well as the antecedents of the offender. In _Ng Soon Kim_, due to the offender’s plea of guilt, which warranted some moderation in sentencing, and the fact that he was a first-time offender, Menon CJ arrived at a final sentence of seven months’ imprisonment. (see \[17\]).

#### Applying the three-step process in Ng Soon Kim

##### (1)   First Step - Sentence under s 323

79     As stated above, the first step of the process requires a determination of the sentence if the hurt had been the subject of a s 323 offence. In the present case, Wong had to be admitted to National University Hospital, where he was diagnosed with right hand traumatic laceration. He then had to undergo right hand debridement surgery and secondary closure of right hand under local anaesthesia on 18 February 2022, and was discharged on 21 February 2022.

80     While counsel suggested that “the harm caused is a minor laceration to a non-vulnerable part of the body”, and that this would qualify as a Band 1 category under the _Low Song Chye_ framework, with respect, such a characterisation was erroneous. Certainly what the victim Wong experienced in terms of injury, which required him to undergo surgery and be warded, cannot merely amount to a “minor hurt” (identified as “bruises, scratches, minor lacerations or abrasions”) under Band 1 of the _Low Song Chye_ framework. Instead, I agreed with the Prosecution that the harm caused, which required surgery and hospitalisation, came within Band 2 of the framework, for which the indicative sentencing range is four weeks’ to six months’ imprisonment.

81     In fact, considering that the present offence took place in 2022, and the maximum prescribed punishment for s 323 offences has been increased from two to three years’ imprisonment since the decision in _Low Song Chye_, there is a strong reason to consider that the indicative sentencing ranges should be adjusted arithmetically to utilise the entire sentencing range of up to three years’ imprisonment. This was, in fact, what the District Judge did recently in _PP v Fei Yi_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGDC 81</span> _(“_**_Fei Yi_**_”)_, to arrive at an indicative sentencing range of between 6 weeks and 9 months’ imprisonment for Band 2 offences (see \[75\] – \[76\] of _Fei Yi_), so as to “have regard to the full breadth of the permitted sentencing range” (see _Low Song Chye_ at \[67\]). The appeal against conviction and sentence in _Fei Yi_ was dismissed by the High Court (see HC/MA 937/2022).

82     All in all, considering the nature and seriousness of the injury, a sentence of four months’ imprisonment would have been appropriate as a starting point.

83     Next, as stated above, in _Ng Soon Kim_, Menon J had considered several other factors that would affect the sentence that would otherwise have been appropriate for a s 323 offence. Specifically, Menon CJ had considered the fact that the offender there had targeted a vulnerable part of the victim’s body (the face), and the fact that it was a road rage case. The result of Menon CJ’s analysis was that a short custodial term of two months would have been justified on the facts had the hurt alone been the subject of a charge brought under s 323. This was apparently about double the maximum indicative sentence of four weeks imprisonment for a Band 1 injury under the _Low Song Chye_ framework.

84     In the present case, there were clearly also factors that should lead to an enhancement of the sentence.

85     First, similar to the situation in _Ng Soon Kim_, the accused here had deliberately targeted a vulnerable part of the victim’s body, i.e. Wong’s head, albeit that the injury finally caused was to Wong’s hand, because Wong had managed to use his hand to block and fend of the attack to his head.

86     Second, while this was not a road rage situation as in _Ng Soon Kim_, I noted that the offence was preceded by the accused’s self-induced consumption of cough syrup and diazepam.

> (i)     As indicated in my oral remarks, I considered this to be a relevant consideration because prior to the commission of this offence in 2022, and based on his treatment history and past offences, in particular the 2019 offence, the accused would have been aware of the effect of such substance abuse on him. Yet the accused continued with such substance abuse which preceded the commission of this offence in 2022. While not identical, I saw similarities in the present scenario - where there was voluntary consumption of cough mixture by the accused who already knew he had a problem with such substance abuse, and who has a known history of such abuse causing psychosis - with self-induced intoxication of alcohol which is a recognised aggravating factor. More so here, since the accused was aware of the possible deleterious effect of such substance abuse on his mental state and subsequent behaviour.

> (ii)     Thus, while not completely analogous, the accused’s actions bring to mind the warning by VK Rajah JA in _Wong Hoi Len v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2009\] 1 SLR(R) 115</span> (“**_Wong Hoi Len_**”) at \[44\] that “Those who voluntarily imbibe alcohol must, in the usual course of events, take full responsibility for their subsequent offending.” I was of the view that a similar consideration should apply to those who voluntarily ingest substances that would **_knowingly cause_** them to have a greater tendency to commit offences, in particular, offences of a violent nature.

87     Third, I also took into account the fact there was some degree of preparation involved in the offence, in that the accused had armed himself with a knife, and had gone to a public place with the deliberate intention of causing hurt. Further, as indicated at \[6\] of the SOF, after his use of the knife to chase after one pedestrian, he would re-wrap it with newspaper, thus effectively hiding the presence of this dangerous weapon from the next potential target. While the accused claimed that a voice had told him to randomly target members of the public by slashing them, hence causing him to arm himself with a knife, I took into account that even if true, this was a state of affairs he himself had brought about likely due to his self-consumption of cough mixture and diazepam (see SOF at \[4\] and discussion at \[86\] above). For the avoidance of doubt, this consideration of preparation by the accused (which was a factor that would have applied even if this was just a s 323 offence), was separate from the dangerous means used to cause the hurt, which is a factor that I considered at the next step of the analysis (see \[89\] – \[90\] below).

88     All in all, similar to the approach of Menon CJ in _Ng Soon Kim_, while the indicative sentence would have been four months’ imprisonment had I considered harm alone, the other matters highlighted above meant that a uplift of the sentence to a custodial term by slightly more than double, to nine months’ imprisonment, would have been justified had the hurt alone been the subject of a charge brought under s 323.

##### (2)   Second Step: Suitable uplift based on the dangerous means used

89     As could be seen from the approach of Menon CJ in _Ng Soon Kim_, this step of the process requires a consideration of the dangerous means used to inflict the injuries, and entails also looking at the potential for harm, as well as the possible alarm to third parties/public alarm that may be caused, as a result of the means used.

90     In this regard, the weapon used by the accused – being a knife intended for slashing - was clearly inherently dangerous. As recognised by the High Court in _Zhai Huilu_, a case cited by the Defence, a knife or cleaver can generally be regarded as likely to cause more harm than a weapon like the cement scraper used in _Zhai Huilu_ (where the sentence imposed was 5 months’ imprisonment).

91     In the present case, the accused had also targeted pedestrians who would be unaware of his harmful intent, and hence would likely not have taken any evasive or defensive measure to protect themselves or guard against being injured by his use of the knife. Further, that the accused had deliberately gone to an open area that was freely accessible by the public, and which, from the CCTV footage, was relatively well frequented by pedestrians and other road users,[\[note: 22\]](#Ftn_22) meant that the potential for harm, and the likely alarm to third parties and the public in general that could have been caused, were all relatively high.

92     In fact, two of his TIC charges (DAC 905088-2022 and DAC 905089-2022), framed as criminal intimidation charges under s 506, involved the accused swinging his knife at two other victims, just before the accused committed the s 324 offence against the victim, Wong. The similarity of the offences in those two TIC charges, with the s 324 offence committed against Wong, was also a further basis for an uplift in the sentence for the s 324 offence (see _PP v UI_ <span class="citation">\[2008\] 4 SLR(R) 500</span> (“**_UI_**”) at \[38\]).

93     For completeness, I would add that I essentially only considered these two TIC charges in sentencing for the accused, as they involved offences committed by the accused around the same time as the s 324 offence, and were carried out in similar circumstances. They were thus more relevant for sentencing than the remaining TIC charges involving the offences committed by the accused against his mother in 2021. The latter were of a different nature, and were of little significance in determining sentence.

94     Separately, the Defence had urged me to consider that due to the limp that the accused was suffering from, the potential harm that he could cause was limited, and that this same factor meant that he was physically incapable of chasing or causing further harm to Wong. While there was some apparent merit to this argument, it was, nonetheless, attenuated by the fact that the accused was situated in an area where significant numbers of unsuspecting members of the public would likely walk pass him, without being on their guard. This situation would thus have given the accused ample opportunity to inflict serious injuries on these victims with his knife, without him necessarily having to approach or to chase after them.

95     All in all, having considered all the above matters, I was of the view that a further uplift of six months’ imprisonment from the sentence assessed at \[88\] - to arrive at a sentence of 15 months’ imprisonment - was warranted.

##### (3)   Third Step: Calibrating on account of other considerations

96     I move on now to consider whether there were other aggravating and mitigating circumstances that may have an effect on sentence.

##### a)    Plea of Guilt

97     In this regard, as far as mitigating factors were concerned, I took note of his plea of guilt, which was a factor that was similar recognised in _Ng Soon Kim_ (see \[17\]), as warranting some moderation in sentencing.

98     While counsel also suggested that the accused’s attempt to surrender to the police thereafter should be given further mitigatory weight, I noted that it was this same “attempt to surrender” that in fact brought about the commission of the subsequent criminal intimidation offences that were the subject matter of two of the proceeded charges (DAC-905090-2022 and DAC-902443-2022), when the accused used the same knife to charge at further victims. All things considered, I did not find this factor to be of any real significance in sentencing.

##### b)    Mental/Psychiatric condition and the need to ensure treatment

99     The Defence also argued that based on the accused’s March 2022 IMH Report, he suffered from substance-induced psychosis, and that there was clear evidence that he was actively psychotic, and that his hallucinations and persecutory delusions would have contributed substantially to the alleged offences by impairing his judgment and impulse control. The Defence went further to argue that the existence of a mental disorder on the part of the offender was always a relevant factor in the sentencing process, and that in the circumstances, the accused should be considered less blameworthy than someone not suffering from a psychiatric condition.

100    With respect, I did not consider the accused’s condition to be in any way mitigatory since, as discussed above, it was clear from the March 2022 IMH Report that the accused’s psychosis was brought about by his own actions in voluntarily and deliberately engaging in substance abuse that in turn brought about his psychotic symptoms. The latter then led to his commission of the offence. In this regard:

> (i)     As noted at \[16\] of the March 2022 IMH Report, “(h)is clinical presentation is consistent with Substance-Induced Psychosis, given his ongoing abuse of various drugs in the period preceding the alleged offences as well as the quick and complete resolution of psychotic symptoms upon abstinence of these drugs”.

> (ii)     Further at \[17\] of the same report, Dr Jason Lee had stated that “(t)here is clear evidence that he was activity psychotic around the time of the alleged offences, and his then hallucinations and persecutory delusions would have contributed substantially to the alleged offences by impairing his judgement and impulse control”.

> (iii)     Indeed, as far as the accused’s psychiatric history was concerned, Dr Jason Lee had noted at \[5\] that his psychotic features such as persecutory delusions and related auditory hallucinations in the past were deemed to be drug-induced and **_not associated_** with primary psychotic disorder such as schizophrenia (emphasis added).

> (iv)     Further, also at \[5\], it was noted that the accused was offered a referral to the National Addictions Management Service after his last admission to IMH on 7 February 2022, but that he chose to be discharged against medical advice on 9 February 2022, and was not seen in IMH thereafter.

Thus, in short, any psychotic symptom experienced by the accused before and when he committed the s 324 offence, would appear to have been brought about by himself when he voluntarily chose to abuse substances that he was clearly aware, from his psychiatric history, could trigger his hallucinations and persecutory delusions. Thus, the resulting substance-induced psychosis was self-induced and could hardly be considered to be mitigatory. In fact, as alluded to above, I considered his action in knowingly abusing substances, against his background and knowledge of his known psychiatric history, to be an aggravating feature. As this was already something that I had already taken into account earlier in assessing sentence, I shall say no more about it.

101    I would also add that while counsel suggested that the case of _Chong Hou En_ stands for the proposition that the existence of a mental disorder on the part of the offender is always a relevant factor in the sentencing process, Chan Seng Onn J, in the same case at \[24\], had also made it clear that “(i)n spite of the existence of a mental disorder on the part of the accused, specific deterrence may remain relevant in instances where the offence is premeditated or where there is a conscious choice to commit the offence.”

102    For completeness, Chan J also made it clear at \[24\] that even where the offender has a significantly impaired ability to appreciate the nature and quality of his actions, and rehabilitation may take precedence, rehabilitation “… does not necessarily dictate a light sentence. The accused could also be rehabilitated in prison”. That said, I was of the view that rehabilitation should not be a significant factor in his case, particularly given the accused’s dismal history of repeated and deliberate substance abuse, which preceded and precipitated his commission of the violent offences.

103    On the related point of the accused’s need for treatment, I noted that the accused did not appear to be serious or capable of addressing the underlying cause of his problems. Quite aside from continuing his practice of substance abuse, based on the various IMH reports, it appeared that the accused did not seem to want to take the necessary medication, or to receive the necessary medical treatment.

104    In _Kong Peng Yee_, a case that I had requested parties to consider, the 68-year-old offender was convicted of culpable homicide not amounting to murder for killing his wife in a brutal and violent manner using a knife and a chopper. He was found to have a mental disorder. In deciding to impose a six years’ imprisonment term on the offender, the Court of Appeal felt that such a period of incarceration will give him “….sufficient time to become accustomed to the new reality of having to take medication in a disciplined manner. This will hopefully be of great benefit to him when he is released and returns to live in an uncontrolled environment where he has the choice regarding his medication.” (see \[100\])

105    In the present case, I was of the view that it may also be appropriate to consider an uplift in the sentence to impress on the accused the importance of adhering to his treatment regime, as well as to provide the environment for him to take his medication and to undergo the necessary medical treatment. This was especially important as the assessment in his CT report is that the risk of re-offending is high due to his predisposition caused by his substance-induced psychosis.

106    That said, I was of the view that any enhancement of sentence should be moderated, in light of the factors cited by the Defence, including the strong family support and close relationship that the accused has with his mother and sister, as well as the physical injuries that the accused suffers from, including those that resulted from his being shot in the arm by the police (see CT report at pages 5- 8). These factors could reduce his risk of re-offending (as noted at the CT report at page 9), and/or the possible severity of injuries he could cause to most members of the public even if he re-offends, except perhaps to victims who are elderly or less mobile. Finally, since the accused was to be sentenced for other offences for which he would also receive significant custodial sentences as well, he would already have to serve a significant length of time in prison. There, he could receive treatment, and hopefully learn to become more disciplined in taking medication. As such, at this stage, I took care to temper any uplift in sentence based on this consideration, so as not to impose a sentence that would be disproportionate.

##### Antecedents

107    The accused has previous convictions spanning many years, including for drug offences, offences involving the use of intoxicating substances, public order offences, and offences of violence.

108    That said, I agreed with counsel that most of his antecedents were not violence related, and also do not have a direct bearing on the current s 324 offence. Even his violence related antecedents were somewhat dated and, from the sentences imposed, do not appear to involve particularly serious offences. Thus, all things considered, I did not think that the accused’s antecedents should have a significant effect on the sentence to impose.

109    All in all, taking into account the mitigating and aggravating factors, and taking care not to double count sentencing factors, I was of the view that a further uplift of the earlier assessed sentence by a further three months’ imprisonment, would be proportionate and fair. This means that after carefully applying all the requisite steps and considerations set out in _Ng Soon Kim_, the accused’s sentence for the s 324 offence should be 18 months’ imprisonment.

110    For completeness, I will deal with the remaining arguments put forward by the Prosecution and the Defence for arguing their respective proposed imprisonment sentences for the s 324 offence.

111    As regards the Prosecution’s argument that the likely imprisonment sentence for the s 324 offence was 36 to 42 months’ imprisonment (including a three month imprisonment sentence in lieu of caning), with respect, I was of the view that this claim was clearly untenable.

> (i)     First, as correctly pointed out by the Defence, the Prosecution’s submission for 36 to 42 months’ imprisonment, was unprecedented. Neither did the Prosecution cite any authority, nor put forward any similar case, where the sentence imposed has come _even remotely close_ to what the Prosecution was seeking.

> (ii)     Second, I was of the view that the Prosecution’s position simply could not be supported when one properly applied the three-step process in _Ng Soon Kim_, taking into account the actual circumstances of the case, and the injury ultimately suffered by Wong. Having discussed the application of _Ng Soon Kim_ in detail above, I will not belabour this point.

> (iii)     Third, going by the data that the Defence had extracted from the SIR on sentences for section 324 offences passed since 22 October 2001, there have been 703 sentences passed, of which there have been only five sentences of imprisonment terms between 40-44 months, and one sentence exceeding 48 months. The Defence pointed out that this meant that the potential sentence the Prosecution was submitting for was in the **99****th****percentile** of sentences for s 324 offences. Further, as correctly pointed out by the Defence, the Prosecution has, with respect, failed to explain why such an extraordinary and extreme imprisonment sentence was justified. To this end, I have reproduced the SIR data, helpfully provided by the Defence, below to illustrate the stark, and in my respectful view, unsupportable position put forward by the Prosecution.

![](data:image;base64,)

> (iv)     Finally, I would add that the Prosecution’s argument that the imprisonment sentence for the s 324 offence should also be increased by three months in lieu of the caning that would otherwise have been imposed on the accused, was also somewhat misconceived. For one, caning is not a mandatory punishment for a s 324 offence, and whether it would have been imposed on the accused was not even properly argued or established on the facts. More importantly, as was made clear by the learned Chief Justice Menon in _Amin bin Abdullah v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] SGHC 215</span> (“**_Amin bin Abdullah_**”), the starting point is that an additional imprisonment term in lieu of caning should _not_ be imposed, unless there are grounds for doing so. This would be the case even if caning is a mandatory part of the sentence: see _Amin bin Abdullah_, at \[54\]. In the present case, the Prosecution has not shown any reason why a departure from the starting point was appropriate, let alone that the additional imprisonment term in lieu of caning, even if appropriate, should come up to three months’ imprisonment. Thus, I did not agree with the Prosecution’s submission for the imposition of this additional term of imprisonment.

112    Dealing now with the vastly contrasting position put forward by the Defence, _viz_, that the sentence should not be more than 9 months’ imprisonment, with respect, and again without repeating my analysis above, I was of the view that the Defence’s position had also failed to take into account all the relevant considerations highlighted in _Ng Soon Kim_, and the other relevant cases and factors I have discussed.

113    Finally, I would add that while the sentence of 18 months’ imprisonment that I have assessed to be appropriate on the facts, may appear relatively high as compared to the sentences imposed in most of the other cases set out in the SIR table for s 324 offences, albeit still much lower than what the Prosecution had advocated (see \[111\] above), I was of the view that this sentence of 18 months’ imprisonment is appropriate and in line with the relevant sentencing principles and authorities that I have discussed at some length above.

### Sentence for the s 506 offences

114    I move on now to consider the two s 506 offences; one directed against the taxi driver, Goh, and the other at the police officer, Tan. Both these offences took place within a short time of each other, and both involved the accused using a knife to commit criminal intimidation against these victims, with the threat, in each case, to be that of causing the victim grievous hurt by charging at that victim while brandishing a knife.

115    To recap, the Prosecution argued that a likely imprisonment sentence would be 18 months’ imprisonment per charge, while the Defence argued that the sentence should be no more than 2 months’ imprisonment per charge. Both parties cited reported authorities to support their respective positions, with the Defence also putting forward SIR data to rebut the Prosecution’s position.

116    However, as regards the cases cited by the Prosecution and the Defence, I found them to be of limited assistance for various reasons.

> (i)     For one, the s 506 charges that the accused faced were both framed under the second limb of the provision, for which the maximum sentence is 10 years imprisonment.

>> a)       This meant that the two of the cases that the Defence cited in support of its sentencing position - namely _Ong Sock Hung_ and _Lwee Kwi Ling Mary_, where the charges were framed under the 1st limb for which the maximum sentence was only two years imprisonment, would clearly be of little relevance.

>> b)       In this regard, I would reiterate the observation made by the Court of Appeal in _Angliss Singapore Pte Ltd v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2006\] 4 SLR(R) 653</span> (“**_Angliss_**”), at \[84\] that “…sentencing judges must take note of the maximum penalty and then apply their minds to determine precisely where the offender’s conduct falls within the spectrum of punishment devised by Parliament.”

>> c)       Thus, as the maximum prescribed custodial term is 10 years imprisonment for the present s 506 offences (2nd limb), I had to calibrate the accused’s sentence with this maximum penalty in mind. This maximum penalty is clearly much higher than the maximum penalty that applied for the offenders in _Ong Sock Hung_ and _Lwee Kwi Ling Mary_. Hence, the sentences that the sentencing judges arrived at for those cases (which would have been limited by the maximum term of 2 years’ imprisonment), would provide little by way of guidance to me in light of the vastly different sentencing perimeters.

> (ii)     As for the case of _Tay Hai Choon_, also cited by the Defence:

>> a)       The offender there was convicted after trial and sentenced to 6 months’ imprisonment. There was an appeal filed by the offender against his conviction and sentence, although the result of the appeal was not apparent from the judgment.

>> b)       Be that as it may, it would appear that while the threat there was to cause death, the Prosecution proceeded under the first limb of s 506 instead, since the sentencing judge noted at \[69\] that “…the prescribed punishment for an offence under section 506 of the Penal Code for the criminal intimidation charge is imprisonment up to 2 years or a fine or both.” In fact, at \[67\] of the judgement, the sentencing judge also noted the concession made by the Prosecution that “…the threat by the accused was intended merely to cause alarm” (as opposed to a threat to cause death or grievous hurt under the 2nd limb of s 506), and it was also apparent from the charge at \[1\] that the Prosecution proceeded on the lesser limb of “intent to cause alarm”.

>> c)       Moreover, it appears from \[68\] that the Prosecution there had merely sought a custodial sentence, without specifying the length of the custodial sentence sought.

>> d)       Needless to say, similar to the cases of _Ong Sock Hung_ and _Lwee Kwi Ling Mary_, as the Prosecution in _Tay Hai Choon_ proceeded on the 1st limb of s 506, for which the maximum prescribed imprisonment was only 2 years, and as the Prosecution there had taken the position that the offender’s intent there was “merely to cause alarm”, _Tay Hai Choon_ again differed vastly from the present case, which was one under the 2nd limb, for which the maximum prescribed imprisonment is 10 years, **and** where the threat was to cause grievous hurt. It would thus again not be appropriate, or fair, to consider the sentence imposed in _Tay Hai Choon_, when determining the sentence to impose in the present case.

> (iii)     I move on now to consider the case of _Tan Kay Beng_, which was a case cited by the Prosecution.

>> a)       Concerning this case, the Prosecution had stated at \[14\] of its ‘Prosecution’s Further Submissions on Sentence’, that it was highlighted to the Court in _Tan Kay Beng_ that “A threat to cause death falls within the second limb. Where the threat to kill is without a weapon, the sentencing range for offenders with no prior record is between six to 12 months’ imprisonment. Where a weapon was used as part of the threat to cause death, a term of two years’ imprisonment was imposed by the High Court in two recent cases.”

>> b)       However, it should be noted that this extract of what was highlighted to the Court in _Tan Kay Beng_ was in fact taken from the _Sentencing Practice in the Subordinate Courts_ (LexisNexis, 2nd Ed, 2003) \[“**Sentencing Practice**”\] at p 217 (see \[45\] of _Tan Kay Beng_). With respect, I did not find the Prosecution’s reference to this extract from the Sentencing Practice to be of much relevance since VK Rajah J, who delivered in the judgement in _Tan Kay Beng_, appeared to have reservations about relying on the actual sentences referred to in above extract. In fact at \[45\], his Honour had stated:

>>> While _prima facie_ it is correct to assert that aggravated criminal intimidation will attract higher punishment the sentence meted out must be tempered by both proportionality and just as crucially by the specific factual matrix. **_I stress in addition that these passages are to be viewed as no more than guidelines and should neither be religiously applied nor adhered to mechanically._** In the final analysis it must be acknowledged that sentencing precedents function purely as an aid so that consistency in sentencing may be maintained. General consistency in sentencing while desirable is not an overriding sentencing consideration. **_The factual matrix always remains paramount._**

\[emphasis added\]

>> c)       What was thus clear from VK Rajah J’s words was that the learned Judge did not actually endorse as a benchmark, or advocate the adoption of a sentencing range of between six to 12 months’ imprisonment where the threat to kill was carried out without a weapon, nor did he endorse the sentence of a two years’ imprisonment range where a weapon was used as part of the threat to cause death. Instead, his Honour’s clear emphasis was that the “factual matrix always remains paramount”.

>> d)       In any event, as the Defence rightly pointed out, even the excerpt from Sentencing Practice referred to in _Tan Kay Beng_ dealt with a threat to cause **death**, rather than a threat to cause grievous hurt, as was the situation in the present case. This was yet another critical distinction, bearing in mind the very wide definition of grievous hurt in the Penal Code (see s 320), which encompasses hurt as “serious” as death, as well as much less serious types of hurt including (even) minor fractures.

117    Thus, to reiterate, I found the cases cited by the Prosecution and Defence to ultimately be of little assistance. Instead, in line with VK Rajah’s guidance in _Tan Kay Beng_ that “(t)he factual matrix always remains paramount”, I considered the particular facts of each of the s 506 offences in the present case to determine the appropriate punishment.

118    In this regard, I first noted that for both offences, the accused had targeted innocent victims who were just performing their respective duties at the material time, _viz_, Goh, the taxi driver, was driving his taxi, and Tan, the police officer, was performing his policing duties. These victims were also arguably persons in ‘protected classes’, thus meriting an appropriately stern sentence to be imposed on offenders who threaten violence against them.

> (i)     In the case of DAC-905090-2022:

>> a)       The victim Goh, the taxi driver, was ferrying the accused to the police station on the accused’s instructions at the time of the incident. In fact, Goh was actually trying to check on the accused, after the latter had fallen off his taxi when attempting to alight, when the accused charged at Goh with his knife at hand. This was the substance of the s 506 offence involving Goh.

>> b)       When Goh managed to escape, the accused did not relent. Instead, he continued to point his knife at Goh even after the latter had got into his taxi and locked the door.

>> c)       In my view, an offence committed against a public transport worker, who by nature of his job, was especially prone to the risk of violence posed by passengers whom he has to interact with as part of their job, called for a deterrent sentence to be imposed to protect such workers (see _Wong Hoi Len_ at \[11\] and \[18\]).

> (ii)     In the case of DAC-902443-2022:

>> a)       The victim Tan was a police officer who was on duty at Clementi Police Division when the accused charged towards him brandishing his knife. This occurred after the police officers, including Tan, had commanded the accused to stop his advance towards them, and to drop his knife (see \[11\] of the SOF).

>> b)       As regards offences against police officers, the three-judge panel in the High Court decision of _Jeffrey Yeo_ had noted at \[48\] that “Police officers are often exposed to violence and aggression in their frontline duties daily. They frequently endanger their lives and risk their personal safety in the discharge of their duties to protect society by maintaining law and order.” In the present case, the threat was also carried out in a public place, at the entrance of the police station no less.

>> c)       I was of the view that such a grave threat, made with a knife against a police officer who was doing his job by ordering the accused to desist from advancing and to drop his knife, and which offence was carried out in clear defiance of authority, must be addressed by a sufficiently stiff imprisonment sentence.

119    Next, I considered that the threat was made with a dangerous weapon, in this case, a knife. While there were no words uttered by the accused towards the victims, Goh and Tan, the accused had charged at both of them with his knife. His actions would have caused grave alarm to them.

120    In addition, as with his s 324 offence, I considered the circumstances in which the s 506 offences were brought about, namely the state of psychosis arising from the accused’s substance abuse. That said, I recognised that in the case of both s 506 offences, it appeared that the accused only came to deal with both victims because he was trying to go to a police station, ostensibly to surrender (see March 2022 IMH Report at \[12\] and \[16\]).

121    Further, I considered the accused’s history of violence and drug/substance abuse although, as with the s 324 offence, I did not find them to be of much significance for essentially the same reasons.

122    In addition, I took into account the accused’s plea of guilt, which has resulted in savings in time and public resources, and which also obliviated the need for the victims to testify.

123    Finally, I considered the SIR data for s 506 offences that the Defence had helpfully provided. I have reproduced the relevant SIR table below.

![](data:image;base64,)

I was of the view that, while each of the s 506 offences clearly merited the imposition of a stiff sentence on the accused, the Prosecution’s proposed sentence of 18 months’ imprisonment per charge was unwarranted particularly, as the Defence had rightly pointed out, when such a sentence could effectively be in the **99****th****percentile** of sentences for section 506 offences. Simply put, the facts would not support the imposition of such a harsh sentence for one offence, let alone for both offences.

124    All things considered, I was of the view that a sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment each, still relatively high according to the SIR data, would be appropriate to take into account the various sentencing considerations in the present case.

### Global imprisonment sentence

125    As regards the global imprisonment sentence that would have been imposed, I had to consider the fact that this was a situation of a multiple offender. Having already assessed the likely imprisonment sentence for each of the four proceeded charges, I then had to consider the other sentencing principles discussed in the High Court cases of _Mohamed Shouffee Bin Adam v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 2 SLR 998</span> (“**_Shouffee_**”), and _PP v Raveen Balakrishnan_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 5 SLR 799</span> (“**_Raveen_**”). These considerations were essentially the one transaction rule, and the totality principle, which includes the need for the sentencing court to take a last look at the facts and circumstances to ensure that the aggregate sentence was sufficient and proportionate to the offender’s overall criminality (see \[98\] of _Raveen_).

126    As regards how the individual sentences should run, the starting point is to decide whether the offences are unrelated, and this is dependent on whether they involve a single invasion of the same legally protected interest. As noted in _Raveen Balakrishnan_ at \[98(b)\], “(a)s a general rule, sentences for unrelated offences should run consecutively, while sentences for offences that form part of a single transaction should run concurrently, subject to the requirement in s 307(1) of the CPC.”

127    In the present case, it was clear that the 332 offence committed in 2019, was distinct from the other three offences committed in 2022. Of the latter three offences, the s 324 offence was also unrelated to the two s 506 offences, and involved the invasion of a different legally protected interest.

128    However, between the two s 506 offences, there was some broad commonality in terms of proximity in time, purpose, location and manner of execution, and I was prepared to consider them to have been committed as part of the same transaction. These meant that the sentences for the s 332 offence and the s 324 offence, and the sentence for one of the s 506 offences, should run consecutively, with the sentence for the remaining s 506 offence running concurrently.

129    As regards which of the two sentences for the s 506 offences should run consecutively, my view was that it would be more appropriate for the sentence for the later offence to run consecutively, as it was committed after but within a very short period of the first s 506 offence, and it was also the last offence committed by the accused out of the eight charges that he faced.

130    In summary, the individual and global imprisonment sentences that would have been imposed for the proceeded charges are set out below.

## _Sim Yeow Kee_: Stage 2 Step 2– Whether the MAS would apply

131    It was common ground that the accused would not qualify for MAS. However, this was but one of the considerations in deciding whether CT should be imposed.

132    As noted by Sundaresh Menon CJ in _Ong Say Kiat_ at \[16\] “…_Sim Yeow Kee_ did not contemplate that CT should automatically be imposed whenever an offender does not qualify for the MAS.” Indeed, in _Ong Say Kiat_, while the respondent would likely not have qualified for the MAS, Menon CJ decided that CT should not be imposed in that case. I will discuss _Ong Say Kiat’s_ case further when dealing with the final step of the _Sim Yeow Kee_ framework below.

## _Sim Yeow Kee_: Stage 2 Step 3– Whether CT would be unduly proportionate

133    As regards this final step of the framework, the Court in _Sim Yeow Kee_ made clear that CT should not be imposed if even imposing the statutorily prescribed minimum term of CT would result in a period of incarceration that would be unduly proportionate to the imprisonment term that would otherwise be imposed. As noted above, in _Sim Yeow Kee_ itself, the Court set aside the CT sentence imposed on the appellant Sim, having assessed that he would only have been sentenced to a period of 42 months of regular imprisonment, and he was also eligible for MAS, as the sentence of even the minimum period of five years’ CT would be unduly disproportionate (see \[114\] of the judgment).

134    In the subsequent case of _Ong Say Kiat_, Menon CJ, applying the framework in _Sim Yeow Kee_, allowed an appeal and set aside a sentence of five years' CT that had been imposed on the respondent who was convicted of theft offences. In its place, Menon CJ imposed a sentence of imprisonment on the respondent equivalent to the time already served. In coming to his decision, Menon CJ assessed the sentencing precedents, the Prosecution’s sentencing position, and the sentence imposed on the accomplice, and decided that “even after applying the principle of escalation”, the sentence that would have been imposed on the respondent would, at its highest, be nine months’ imprisonment (see \[13\]). As alluded to above, his Honour arrived at his decision even though he noted that the respondent would likely not have qualified for the MAS.

135    Instead, on the facts of the case, Menon CJ decided that CT would be inappropriate because it would be unduly disproportionate to the imprisonment term. Specifically, at \[18\], Menon CJ stated:

> In the present case, the minimum term of CT mandated by s 304(1) of the CPC (that is, five years) was very substantially in excess of the likely imprisonment term for the respondent' s offence, which would have been nine months at most (see \[13\] above). It was therefore clear that the imposition of CT would have resulted in a period of incarceration that was seriously or unduly disproportionate to the imprisonment term which would otherwise likely have been imposed.

136    In the present case, as with the first appellant in _Sim Yeow Kee_, and the respondent in _Ong Say Kiat_, in view of the likely imprisonment sentence of 33 months for the accused, “…the imposition of CT would have resulted in a period of incarceration that was seriously or unduly disproportionate to the imprisonment term which would otherwise likely have been imposed” (per Menon CJ in _Ong Say Kiat)._

137    Further, as rightly pointed out by the Defence, it was also because CT would be disproportionate, in light of the likely imprisonment sentences, that the courts declined to impose CT in the case of _Ibrahim bin Bajuri_ and also the case of _Joseph Doray s/o Saverymuthu (_see \[43\] above).

138    I would conclude my discussion of _Sim Yeow Kee_ by dealing with the Prosecution’s argument that CT should be imposed, _inter alia_, for the protection of the public, the authorities and even the accused’s own family. [\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23) At \[87\] of _Sim Yeow Kee_, Menon CJ provided this timely reminder:

> “…**_the object of preventing crime alone would not afford a sufficient basis for the court to impose CT unless it is also satisfied that the longer term of incarceration mandated under the CT regime would be expedient for the offender’s reformation. A focus on crime prevention alone would in fact result in the CT regime being virtually indistinguishable from the PD regime_**, under which (assuming the offender satisfies the technical requirements set out in s 304(2) of the CPC) PD is to be imposed where it is “expedient for the protection of the public” to do so.”

\[emphasis added\]

## Conclusion

139    In light of the analysis above, it was clear that a sentence of CT should not be imposed. Instead, the appropriate sentence would be a global imprisonment term of 33 months, as set out at \[130\] of these Grounds of Decision. This was thus the sentence that I imposed. I also backdated this sentence to 17 February 2022 as this was the date of his arrest.

140    I am of the view that the global sentence imposed on the accused is fair and proportionate, and has taken into account the relevant sentencing principles, sentencing considerations, and sentencing precedents.

141    Finally, it leaves me to thank the Prosecution and the Defence for their detailed and passionate arguments, and for the case authorities, SIR data, and reports that they have usefully provided and referred to in the course of their submissions. As can be seen from these Grounds of Decision, I have made extensive references to parts of their submissions and to the materials that they put forward. Even though I ultimately did not agree with the proposed sentences of either party, or with some of the arguments that they put forward, I appreciated the efforts put in by parties, and the materials they provided, which have all been of immense assistance to this court in arriving at the appropriate sentence in this case.
